With games wanting to use Raytraced lighting and other gimmicks for dynamic graphic fidelity and games moving away from static highly optimized scenes, there is no getting around anymore needing frame generation to get decent FPS. The real issue then becomes do the upscaled resolution generated frames look good enough compared to straight rasterized frames scenes as a trade-off, including any issues related to movement, even when operating in 4k?   If not, then users need to fight back against it.

Just going based on the latency comparisons you can see at 4:38, it's looking like the pure non-AI raster performance increases here are very small.   Doing some rounding, the 35 ms latency of the 5090 gives 1/0.035 ~= 29 natural frames, where the 4090 37 ms gives 1/0.037 ~= 27 natural frames. This seems pretty in line with the original raw natural framerate numbers we've seen in Nvidia's own material from the 5090 and 4090 videos using no AI frame generation. Basically, no matter how many AI frames you cram in, the latency will still feel like 27fps without the natural frames to work with. Even if the AI frames look absolutely perfect, I feel we have hit a point of diminishing returns here.

I just want to put this in to try and explain DLSS and frame gen to people who don't fully understand.              "DLSS uses AI algorithms to upscale lower-resolution images, significantly enhancing visual fidelity while maintaining high performance. By rendering games at a lower resolution and then upscaling them, DLSS can significantly increase frame rates. This is especially beneficial for demanding games, allowing for smoother gameplay on high settings. DLSS can adapt its quality settings based on the performance of the hardware, ensuring an optimal balance between visual fidelity and frame rates. While DLSS generally provides high-quality images, it can sometimes introduce artifacts, such as blurriness or ghosting, especially in fast-moving scenes. DLSS operates in real-time, allowing it to provide upscaled images while the game is being played. This is crucial for maintaining a smooth gaming experience. DLSS does not introduce significant input latency. While any processing can potentially add a slight delay, NVIDIA has optimized DLSS to minimize this impact, ensuring that it remains responsive during gameplay."              So this being said, every frame from the game is being rastered by the GPU in a lower resolution and then in real time it is being upscaled by the GPU to you're monitors resolution, depending on the DLSS quality setting you pick, the native resolution is a different percentage of the native resolution. This means that DLSS is not the problem with so called "fake frames" DLSS is actually a really good system that NVIDIA has created.                Frame gen is the Fake frames that get hated on but, that being said Frame Gen has its place in gaming. If you want to play a single player or even multiplayer game that does not rely on fast precise inputs or you're the type of person who is not sensitive to latency it can be a great thing. I personally use DLSS on most games as I have a 4080 and a 5120x1440p super ultrawide monitor, that is a lot of native pixels to push on very high settings.                 I have only used frame gen on Flight Simulator as the title is very demanding and doesn't require me to worry about input latency, and in that use case it is very nice in my eyes. Now when I

4:37 Playing Cyberpunk with the new frame generation feature essentially feels like a DLSS 4 demo. It doesn't provide a clear comparison to the performance of the RTX 4090. With PCL values of 35 and 37, the estimated framerate is around 30 FPS at 1080p with DLSS Performance mode. While you might see "263" or "125" FPS, the latency is comparable to running at 30 FPS. Ideally, 263 FPS should result in approximately 3.8 milliseconds of latency, and 125 FPS should yield around 8 milliseconds. However, the actual latency is 5-10 times higher than if the game were running natively at those framerates. This makes playing any FPS game with such latency quite challenging, especially with a mouse and keyboard.  Don't be fooled‚ÄîNVIDIA is using DLSS 4 to mask the actual performance of the cards. Frame generation is cool tech and has decent use if the base framerate is at least 60 and is used on slower-paced games, likely with a controller. However, NVIDIA is advertising an actual performance jump of at most 30-45% as a doubling, without taking into account the input latency cost of frame generation. You can see on NVIDIA's 5090 page that, assuming the settings are comparable, the 5090 was getting around 27 FPS without DLSS or frame generation enabled at native 4K, with the 4090 getting around 22 FPS.

This trend of treating consumers as quasi-beta testers is deeply frustrating, especially when companies have the resources and historical examples of doing it right. The 'win-win' for them‚Äîreduced development costs and the ability to fix issues on the fly‚Äîoften becomes a lose-lose for players who endure incomplete launches, constant updates, and the risk of games becoming unplayable due to server dependency.  Take Halo as a perfect example. Bungie, under Microsoft‚Äôs umbrella, delivered a polished and optimized game across multiple systems back in 2003, even without today‚Äôs advanced tools or infrastructure. This shows that the current issues aren‚Äôt about technical limitations‚Äîthey‚Äôre about misplaced priorities and business strategies.  What‚Äôs even worse is the push toward online content for single-player experiences. Multiplayer dependency is understandable, but locking single-player titles behind servers feels exploitative. The nostalgia for self-contained, well-tested games like Halo or older Call of Duty titles is bittersweet‚Äîthose games didn‚Äôt just work; they excelled.  To add insult to injury, this trend even impacts hardware adoption. The pressure to upgrade just to 'keep up' with poorly optimized software is absurd. Hardware diversity and innovation used to be exciting, but now, it feels overshadowed by teams who prioritize marketing tactics over user experience. It‚Äôs bad not just for consumers, but also for reviewers. I miss the days when hardware and software came together to truly elevate gaming.

For those who are appreciating NVIDIA for there so called *5000 series*, it uses DLSS 4 technology i.e. using AI for frame generation. It means if the graphics card generated 1 frame the AI will have a look at that frame and generate 3 additional frames which are predicted by AI till the second frame is generated by the graphics card. It means your gameplay will be 75% AI powered and 25% real. So if a game runs at 60 FPS, using DLSS it will run at 240 FPS giving 180 FAKE FPS and surely increasing latency. And that's the reason they are selling it cheap.

Honestly, three out of the four frames are AI generated. They are not "real" frames. If you want to find the real framerate, divide the FPS by four. Let's use 175 FPS. The ComputerBase review provided more insight into the power efficiency curve of the 5090 vs the 4090 at 4K. When they are both limited to 450W, the 5090 is 17% faster, versus the 24% that was measured at the full 575W. At 400W, the 5090 is around 12% faster than the stock 4090. However, this analysis has the caveat that it's rare for the 4090 to pull the entire available 450W (as evidenced by the fact that it only loses a mere 2% on average at 350W vs 450W), so it's not perfectly apples-to-apples. Though, the 5090 is clearly capable of doing slightly more with the same power budget (at least at reasonable power limits) compared to the 4090, but still not a terribly impressive generational uplift.

When Nvidia is chalking out a new product range, there is a maximum die size that they can produce cost effectively at scale. Assuming Moore's law is mostly trucking along, it's around 600mm2 and 40% faster than last gen. For this example, lets say a new generation die is 600mm2 and has 10,000 cores and is given the nomenclature EX-102 (102 notates that highest end non data center silicon)  The tradition would then follow that their Titan and Quadro cards would get 95%-100% of the number of cores that this full 102 die has to offer (because they are using this die). So in this example they would have 10,000 cores.  The 80ti - Also on a 102 - 93% of the 10,000 cores, so around 9300 cores.  The 80 - 102/103 - 66-80% of the 102's full cores. But here's the thing. Sometimes these end up on 103. A smaller, cheaper, die. The other skus up until this point have fused off sections of the 102 die. The 103 is a different piece of silicon entirely. While it might seem unfair to compare them, they are still the same in architecture and scale linearly in some workloads. In any case, we would expect 66% of the cores or in this example 6600 cuda cores.  The 70 class cards are normally 50% and built on 104 so 5000 cores  The 60 class on 106 and hovers around the low 30s or 3000 cores  -----------------------------------------------  This is the expectation as it has been set for the better part of 15 years. It has only been until last gen [4000 series] that we received cards that were substantially different.  The last 90 sku was 87% of the full 102 die. Substantially less than a normal 80ti or titan but curiously, significantly more money. The 80ti, which used to give you the most silicon for the money (again around 90%) is now gone and replaced with the 4080 super, which was 55%. A noticeable drop in the amount of silicon. The standard 4080 even worse at 52%. The 4070 is a shocking 32%.  Using the data I've listed above, it is clear to see that Nvidia has merely moved their entire stack down to make room for their 90 class cards. Again... these 90 cards have no substantial architecture differences that justifies the creation of a new sku. They aren't substantially more silicon. No

It' really simple. None of the frames discussed are fake. "Frame Gen" is just marketing fluff for motion interpolation between rendered source frames. Frames Per Second / Frame Time conventionally was used a metric to indicate the "responsiveness" of the rendering of realtime graphics. If you mix motion interpolation frames into that metric it doesn't convey the same meaning anymore. The sensation of having a higher fps and direct correlation to how responsive the game feels is no longer 1:1. Frame interpolation has been a thing for videos for a long time but you won't see blockbuster movies advertising a 240fps cinema experience because the movie was shot at 24fps and your interpolated 9 additional frames in between (that will have artefacts). It would come across as a tacky post-processing effect, because it is.

6:50 Professional "AI Dork" here... The 5090 having 32GB VRAM is basically useless. It will not be able to run hardly anything that the 4090 can't already run blisteringly fast  For example, my 3090 can generate text with a maximum size model that can fit in 24GB VRAM at over 120 words per second across 4 streams, which is already monumentally faster than any normal person can read  Now, the 5090 can fit damn near no bigger models (cause 32GB VRAM is still pitifully small for LLMs, not even being able to fit a full precision 20B param model when we have models that are 600B-1T+ in size now), but at an even faster speed, which basically nobody wants. The limit of quality for local AI is not speed. It hasn't been for a very long time. The limit is quality and network size, something of which the 5090 will do basically nothing to improve.  So in essence, you can't really run anything too much better on the 5090, and now instead of generating at 3x the speed you can read, you can gen at 4x the speed you can read... groundbreaking  So yeah, the 32GB VRAM for the 5090 is the absolute bare minimum they could have given, and will still be a severe artificial limit on how useful the 5090 will ever be. A 3 gen old original A6000, which is like 1/5th the speed of the 5090 is far more useful, simply for the fact it has 48GB VRAM. People want better quality, not more speed when you are already way faster than you need to be

The 50 series is a huge letdown. They're good cards of course, but the way Nvidia talks about this stuff, you always expect a revolution, and you get an evolution. These are 40 series cards with a crapload of power pumped into them to keep stable. This is not exactly ideal. Nvidia is way too distracted with side projects. They've got 5000 features they're working on, and only a small handful of them ever pan out. Don't get me wrong, I love Nvidia. If it weren't for them, we'd be in a world of hurt. However, when it comes to just raw 3d rendering, we're getting screwed. I bought a GTX1080 for $500 in 2017, and today that will buy me a 4070. The 4070S is another $120. 8 years and only 85% improvement. That's insane. There was almost the same improvement from the 900 series to the 10 series, and that was 2 years. People always ask me "dude how can you still run a GTX1080 and a 7700k?!?!" and it's because I have a Gsync 144hz display, and in competitive games we all turn down graphics settings so I get lots of frames, and in games that aren't competitive, I have Gsync. So really nothing will change yet. Not until I can afford a card that will drive 1440p at 240hz+ for affordable prices. I'm not paying a thousand dollars for a graphics card. I have other hobbies.

One way to explain the tensor cores and neural shading is as follows: The neural networks can be used to approximate extremely complicated functions for which we can't just write simple equations. However, we can create those networks with a simple procedure merely by showing them many examples. So for example we can show it what rocky terrain looks like at all levels of detail, and the network will learn how to do that, using less data (just what the network's values are) than trying to store all the terrain (what the network computes as output). It's sort of like procedural terrain, but learned instead of programmed. The tensor cores are what are used to efficiently compute those trained neural networks on the GPU. They're not the same as geometry or pixel shaders, so they need their own specialized cores for the task.

I think the simplest way to explain convolutional neural networks is: for every pixel, a new pixel value is calculated based on its nearby neighbours. E.g. if every pixel is replaced with the average of its neighbours, you get a blur effect. Think of a visual illusion where you see some broken lines and your mind fills in the missing parts of the line, that's how these CNNs would be used to preserve detail as they upscale. However, it's a lot of computation, and a challenge to preserve scene integrity because the neighbourhoods are small compared to the entire scene. Transformer models allow arbitrary areas to serve as context when computing new pixel values; think of it as like having configurable neighbourhoods to input to that computation. E.g. when trying to upscale the left side of a road in the game's scene, that computation can also refer to the right side of the road all the way across the screen.

CNNs are faster / more efficient than transformers, partly due to locality bias. The "scaling" Nvidia mentions is that transformers get better with more parameters / training in a way that CNNs don't. So the transformer is likely larger than the CNN, making it even more impressive that they are able to run in real time.

For a GPU to render/draw the "3 Fake Frames in between", it must already know what the "Next Real Frame" looks like. This is the real issue! So for a Game being Faked into 4x fps, the GPU has to hold back the next frame that it already knows about to be able to draw the next 3 fake frames. Consider 6fps raw, 1/60th of a second it holds that next frame back, it is adding 16.66 ms of latency to every rendered frame.  This would easily be seen on camera. Why is no one demonstrating this!

When we hit the one nanometer or smaller transistors, the weight transistors work kind of completely falls apart. Transistor is more or less work like a switch and when we apply an electrical signal to that switch it turns on for a 1 or 0. When we hut those really small sizes, the electrons have a much higher chance to just quantum tunnel through the transistor defeating its entire purpose.

Hey, just some feedback regarding the graphs.  I think it would be nice to have a better indicator to more easily differentiate the specific card which is being reviewed, especially since this is arguably the most important part of these graphs, where the card being reviewed sits in relation to the other cards on the market. The green dot is nice, but it could still be more clear (having it be a different colour, more saturated, white border/background, etc), especially when there are multiple different cards highlighted in this way. (This goes along with the feedback which I'm sure you have seen in the other comment/s, about having the whole row highlighted to more easily see which specific card you are drawing attention to, rather than having to pan across from the dot on the right to the name on the left).  Also, I feel like having the 1% lows for every card in the fps graphs creates more clutter than it adds value to the graphs (at least for me), as in almost every case the 1% lows are roughly the same percentage lower for every card. I found myself essentially ignoring them completely, and instead mainly just looking at the overall length of the bar, which ended up just being the average because it is longer. Personally, I the main thing I gained from the 1% lows bar is the difference between the average frame rates and 1% lows for each individual card, which is good for the card being reviewed, but isn't very useful for the 3090 when the review is focused on the 5080. If there is a particular case in which the 1% lows show a significantly different story to the averages, I think it would be better to instead mention this specifically, alongside a graph displaying primarily (or only) the 1% lows. Maybe an option would by to only show 1% lows for the card in the review, which would both help differentiate the card being reviewed from the rest of the cards, remove clutter, and, in my opinion, retain the most valuable bit of information that 1% lows show (how they compare to the fps average of the card being reviewed).  Last thing, it would be nice to have some way to more easily differentiate the different generations of card. The most frequent questions I find myself asking are "how does this compare to the nvidia cards from the last generation", "how does this compare the other nvidia cards of this generation" and "how does this compare to amd". All of these would be much easier to answer if the generations were grouped in some

That is just like expecting Moore's law to be valid in perpetuity (Moore's law is dead).  There is a limit somewhere, and instead of a linear graph, it should be more like a log scale (with occasional stair-steps when new technology enables large jumps in performance). The issue we're having with these cards is unrealistic expectations versus price, not the card.

No, it does not break the laws of physics. A 600W GPU can produce less heat than a 400W GPU if it is more efficient in converting electrical power into useful work (such as rendering frames) rather than waste heat.  How Is This Possible?  Higher Efficiency Components  Newer GPUs use advanced silicon fabrication processes (e.g., smaller nanometer nodes like 3nm or 5nm).  These processes improve power efficiency, meaning more energy is used for computation rather than heat dissipation.  Better Power Delivery & VRMs  Higher-quality voltage regulation modules (VRMs) and power management techniques reduce wasted energy in conversion.  Advanced Cooling Solutions  Vapor chamber cooling, better heatsinks, and fans can dissipate heat more effectively.  This means even if total power consumption is higher, the GPU surface feels cooler due to better heat dissipation.  Dynamic Power Management  Modern GPUs optimize power usage dynamically, consuming only what is needed per workload, reducing unnecessary heat generation.  Example:  A 400W GPU with 75% efficiency wastes 100W as heat (400W √ó 25%).  A 600W GPU with 90% efficiency wastes 60W as heat (600W √ó 10%).  Even though the 600W GPU draws more power, it generates less heat overall because it converts more of that power into useful work rather than waste heat.

I feel like this is because games aren't requiring faster data speeds..... they're requiring more data at once, per transfer. Software is outpacing elements of hardware in relation to the system as a whole. Look at the one spec that sets the 4090/5090/7900XTX apart from the rest.... Bus size. I feel like we've reached the limit for a single frame of what can be rasterized on camera given the current state of AAA optimization standards with the addition of ray tracing data.   Were going to be forced to accept AI eventually or someone is going to have to figure out a way to greatly widen the 'freeways' on our mother boards. It almost feels like Nvidia has contracts with developers to collude.   AMD needs to find a way to make their own mother boards with built in memory. If they can make a special CPU that can communicate with a far greater bus width in one of their GPU's.. I have a feeling it would solve the problem of low frame rates with Ray Tracing. Our bus sizes are just enough for 4k, add in Ray Tracing data and now for the complete frame, the data needs two trips for one frame. All DLSS is doing is freeing up bus space by lowering the resolution so the ray tracing data can fit across the bus at the same time as everything else and finish the frame in one trip. AMD doesn't need AI or DLSS, they can control both ends of the stick CPU - GPU. Nvidia can't. and I feel like Nvidia knows this, hence why they are locking down developers like Sony does to promote AI.. It allows Nvidia to increase frames, without destroying compatibility  raising bus speeds.. you would need proper CPU's, motherboards & memory (and probably more stuff I don't know) to do so. I think this is also why their doing this crap with TAA. It's all a solution to work around forcing people to upgrade their entire PC's with special motherboards/memory/cpu.  If the bus width is the amount of data at once (single signal) the lanes from your GPU to CPU can transfer..... I look at it like pipes with water... eventually you won't be able to increase the flow rate with pressure alone,  you would need to widen the pipes. When a single frame now requires both image rasterization data (that's now unoptimized) AND ray tracing data, you run out of room. If data is water you've now got a higher flow rate

Frame generation perfectly described. 10:16 If you can render high frames natively, you can render frame generations.... but don't really need it. remember: dlss is upscaling and frame generation is making fake ones. Similar, but different. Dlss is very useful and works well, but frame generation doesn't look as good and adds a lot of latency which makes the game less responsive. Reflex does actually help mitigate it, but it is still more responsive to play with no frame generation at all.

It's actually worth mentioning that some of the 'weirdness on the edges of fast moving objects' that you see and show seems to be motion blur artifacts, not DLSS artifacts. The way motion blur and lens blur works in games is, as everything, very faked, it usually is only supplied with information that can be gathered from 1 single frame - depth maps and pixel velocity maps. And since it does not know what's behind the object that needs to be blurred, plus some other issues like overlaying and opacity, it often results in weird artifacts at the edges of blurred objects.  So to make a fair test it should be made between True frames rendered without DLSS and with DLSS, with all other settings equal. Then if you see artifacts on non DLSS render too - you can tell it's not caused by DLSS specifically.

Without shaders most games would run really fast since rasterization is really well optimized.  I purpose a list of objects and how long its been since their shadowmap was updated, then with the time left between frames the card can work through the list and update the oldest shadowmaps first. Haven't really finished the video. The problem with the 5090 is that most of the frames will be generated by AI. It is good, right? Well, in single-player games that revolve around YOUR hardware and YOUR software, it is a massive spike in performance for most games when you talk about smoothness of the game. Now, for any MP game that relies on constant data from your computer and is reliant mostly on the server getting the data and sending you the data, it doesn't affect anything. If your software, on your PC generates additional 3 frames between the in-game frames, the server just DOESNT CARE. It will still utilize only the frames between the ones you generated. It doesn't care, it won't use and your visual smoothness is exactly that, - visual smoothness. They haven't actually increased performance, they added fake frames between the real frames, which doesn't equal performance in any way. And it is useful only in SP games that do not rely on client-server interaction. The servers won't use your fake frames and they don't care.
